<h1>Puppy Vaccination Schedule: What Your Puppy Needs and When</h1>
<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">Puppy vaccines protect against diseases that can be fatal, particularly in the critical window before a puppy's immune system matures. The timing of the schedule isn't arbitrary &mdash; it's designed around the biology of maternal antibody decline and the immune system's ability to respond to vaccines at each age.</p>

<div class="hero-note"><strong>The core concept:</strong> Puppies receive maternal antibodies through their mother's milk. These antibodies protect early on but also interfere with vaccines &mdash; they neutralize the vaccine before the puppy's immune system can respond. The series of shots at multiple intervals is designed to catch the window when maternal antibodies have declined enough for the vaccine to work.</div>

<h2>Core vaccines: required for all puppies</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Vaccine</th><th>Timing</th><th>Protects against</th></tr>
<tr><td>DHPP (Distemper, Hepatitis, Parvovirus, Parainfluenza)</td><td>6-8 weeks, 10-12 weeks, 14-16 weeks</td><td>Four serious viral diseases</td></tr>
<tr><td>Rabies</td><td>12-16 weeks (law varies by state)</td><td>Rabies (fatal, transmissible to humans)</td></tr>
</table>
<p>The DHPP vaccine is sometimes called DA2PP or DA2PPV depending on the manufacturer. The components are essentially the same. Parvovirus is the most critical &mdash; it kills unvaccinated puppies rapidly and is extremely common in environments where unvaccinated dogs congregate.</p>

<h2>Non-core vaccines: based on lifestyle and risk</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Vaccine</th><th>Consider if...</th></tr>
<tr><td>Bordetella (kennel cough)</td><td>Dog will board, go to dog parks, or doggy daycare</td></tr>
<tr><td>Leptospirosis</td><td>Outdoor access to water sources, wildlife exposure</td></tr>
<tr><td>Lyme</td><td>Lives in or visits tick-endemic areas</td></tr>
<tr><td>Canine Influenza</td><td>Frequent dog-to-dog contact, travel</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>The complete timeline</h2>
<p><strong>6-8 weeks:</strong> First DHPP. Many breeders or rescues administer this before the puppy comes home. Confirm in the paperwork whether it was given and the exact date.</p>
<p><strong>10-12 weeks:</strong> Second DHPP. This is the first appointment you'll likely schedule with your own vet. Bordetella can start here if relevant to lifestyle.</p>
<p><strong>14-16 weeks:</strong> Third DHPP + Rabies. This is the last core puppy shot. Some vets give a fourth DHPP at 16 weeks if the puppy received the first dose very early (before 8 weeks).</p>
<p><strong>12-16 months:</strong> First annual boosters for all core vaccines. After this, DHPP typically goes to every 3 years; rabies varies by local ordinance (some require annual, most accept triennial).</p>

<h2>What to watch for after vaccines</h2>
<p>Mild responses are normal and expected: soreness at the injection site, mild lethargy for 24-48 hours, decreased appetite the day of. These are immune system responses, not problems.</p>
<p>Allergic reactions are rare (1 in 10,000 vaccinations) but serious. Watch for facial swelling, hives, vomiting, collapse, or difficulty breathing within 30-60 minutes of vaccination. This is why vets recommend waiting in the parking lot for 10-15 minutes post-vaccination for puppies receiving their first shot of each type.</p>

<div class="callout"><strong>Socialization vs vaccine protection:</strong> The critical socialization window is 8-16 weeks. Complete vaccine protection doesn't exist until 2 weeks after the final DHPP at 14-16 weeks. Avoiding all socialization until fully vaccinated is too late for the socialization window. The practical approach: controlled, low-risk socialization (vaccinated dogs, clean private environments) before the series is complete. Avoid dog parks, pet store floors, and unknown dogs until after the final shot.</div>
